  <p>Most misunderstandings at work aren't caused by difficult people. They're caused by good people misreading each other, every day, without knowing they're doing it.</p>
  <p>People Make Sense is a two-workshop program that fixes the misreading. The first workshop helps people understand the lens they're looking through, and the lens everyone else is looking through too. The second helps them understand what happens because of it: how that lens quietly colors the way we read everyone around us. Together, they give a company something most never get: a shared language for how people actually work.</p>
  <p class="lead">Most companies start here.</p>

  <h3>Workshop 1, Seeing Yourself Clearly</h3>
  <p><em>Why people make sense.</em> Every person on a team is paying attention to something different. One walks into a meeting tracking the goal. Another is tracking the tension in the room. A third is tracking whether the plan has been thought through. Same meeting, three different experiences of it.</p>
  <p>In this workshop, participants discover their own patterns, motivations, communication style, conflict tendencies, and blind spots. They learn the lens they're looking through and why they respond the way they do. What once felt confusing about themselves, and about others, starts to make sense.</p>
  <p>The shift is simple to say and significant to work beside: "That person is difficult" becomes "That person is solving for something different than I am." People become easier to work with because they finally make sense.</p>

  <h3>Workshop 2, Seeing Others Clearly</h3>
  <p><em>Why misunderstandings make sense.</em> The first workshop is about the lens you look through. This one is about what happens because of it.</p>
  <p>Most conflict begins long before the conversation. It begins the moment we start filling in the blanks, assigning motives, predicting reactions, becoming certain about things we don't actually know. By the time something looks like a communication problem, it has often been an interpretation problem for a while.</p>
  <p>Participants learn how misunderstandings get created, how stories become certainty, and how to separate behavior from interpretation. Not the general idea that you misread people, but the actual misreading: <em>I thought you were checked out, and you were thinking it through. I thought you were attacking the plan, and you were protecting it.</em></p>

  <Figure max={600} caption="The same few seconds of someone in a meeting. Three stories form before anyone has said a word. Most conflict starts right here.">
    <StorySnap />
  </Figure>
  <p>People understand how they misunderstand. And once they do, conflict starts getting prevented instead of repeated. Fewer meetings end in two versions of what was decided. The team spends less energy managing each other and more of it on the work.</p>

  <h3>One program, two layers</h3>
  <p>The order matters, and the reason is practical. People have to understand their own lens before they can see how it colors the way they read everyone else. <em>Seeing Yourself Clearly</em> does that first work and gives the team a shared language. <em>Seeing Others Clearly</em> comes second because it asks more, it's easier to understand how you operate than to catch yourself misreading someone in real time. By the second workshop, the team trusts the language and is ready to turn it outward, onto the moments that actually cause friction.</p>
  <p>Most companies run the two a few weeks to a few months apart, which gives the first language time to settle into daily use before the second layer arrives.</p>

  <h3>What's included</h3>
  <p>Every participant completes an Enneagram assessment before the first workshop and receives a personalized type packet, so the learning starts specific rather than general.</p>
  <p>The program comes with the materials that keep it alive after the sessions end: type tiles, at-a-glance communication and conflict cards, information booklets, and company posters that keep the shared language visible where the work happens.</p>
  <p class="lead">The workshop is one day. The language is permanent.</p>
